**Abstract:**
Essay dated August 31, 1993, titled "Draft 2: The Greek Notion of Truth." The document examines the Greek conception of truth as adaequatio mentis ad rem, analyzing the distinction between theoretical knowledge (of universal, necessary objects) and practical knowledge (of particulars by exposed agents). It argues that practical judgment results in action, not mere assent, and that only good people can make correct practical judgments. Explores the vicious circle in ethical theory: admirable behavior derives from cultural habituation, not pure rational discovery.

**AI Recommendation:** Important theoretical essay on Greek epistemology; develops distinction between theoretical and practical knowledge foundational to the Chantilly project.

